  "text": "Django's migration squashing compliance system is implemented across seven core modules in the django/db/migrations package, along with the squashmigrations management command.\n\n**Squash Migration Generator** (django/core/management/commands/squashmigrations.py:Command.handle)\nThe `Command` class in squashmigrations.py is the primary entry point for generating squashed migrations. It loads all migrations to be squashed, extracts their operations and dependencies, applies optimization if requested, and creates a new Migration subclass with the `replaces` attribute set to list all replaced migration keys. The handler creates a MigrationWriter to serialize this new migration to disk (lines 179-209).\n\n**Replaced-Migrations Tracking** comprises multiple interrelated components:\n- django/db/migrations/migration.py (Migration class, line 42): Defines the `replaces` attribute as a list of migration names that this migration replaces\n- django/db/migrations/writer.py (MigrationWriter.as_string(), lines 194-197): Serializes the replaces attribute into the migration file template\n- django/db/migrations/loader.py (MigrationLoader class): Manages tracking of all replacing migrations in the `replacements` dict (line 293), identifies them during disk loading (line 297-298)\n- django/db/migrations/recorder.py (MigrationRecorder class): Maintains the django_migrations table with records of applied migrations via the `applied_migrations()` method (lines 84-97)\n\n**Dependency Graph Validation After Squashing** operates through several graph methods:\n- django/db/migrations/graph.py (MigrationGraph.validate_consistency(), line 198-200): Ensures no DummyNode instances remain in the graph. When migrations with missing dependencies are encountered, DummyNode instances are created as placeholders. After replacements are processed, this method checks that all such dummy nodes have been replaced, otherwise raising NodeNotFoundError\n- django/db/migrations/graph.py (MigrationGraph.ensure_not_cyclic(), lines 271-294): Performs cycle detection using a depth-first search algorithm to prevent circular dependency chains from being introduced during squashing\n- django/db/migrations/graph.py (MigrationGraph.remove_replaced_nodes(), lines 125-159): When a squash migration replaces others, this method removes the replaced nodes from the graph and remaps all dependencies that pointed to them to instead point to the replacement node\n- django/db/migrations/graph.py (MigrationGraph.remove_replacement_node(), lines 161-196): The inverse operation - handles the case where a replacement migration cannot be used (e.g., when only partially applied) by removing it and remapping children back to the replaced nodes\n- django/db/migrations/loader.py (MigrationLoader.build_graph(), lines 274-342): Orchestrates the entire graph building process, calling validate_consistency() after all replacements are processed (line 313) and ensure_not_cyclic() afterward (line 342)\n\n**Squash Completeness Check** validates that squashed migrations are properly applied:\n- django/db/migrations/executor.py (MigrationExecutor.check_replacements(), lines 294-308): Called after every migration execution to mark replacement migrations as applied when all of their replaced migrations have been applied. This handles the case where a new squash migration is deployed to a system that already had all its replaced migrations applied\n- django/db/migrations/executor.py (MigrationExecutor.record_migration(), lines 268-277): When a replacement migration is applied, this method recursively records the applied status of all individual replaced migrations in the database\n- django/db/migrations/loader.py (MigrationLoader.all_replaced_applied(), lines 372-384): Recursively checks whether all migrations that a squash migration replaces are in the applied set, handling nested squashed migrations\n- django/db/migrations/loader.py (MigrationLoader._resolve_replaced_migration_keys(), lines 224-233): Recursively resolves the complete set of replaced migrations, accounting for squashed migrations that themselves replace other squashed migrations\n- django/db/migrations/loader.py (MigrationLoader.replace_migration(), lines 235-272): Orchestrates the replacement process by determining whether the replacement migration can be used (all or none of replaced migrations applied) versus partial application scenarios that require different graph handling\n- django/db/migrations/loader.py (MigrationLoader.check_consistent_history(), lines 344-370): Validates that no applied migration has unapplied dependencies, with special handling for squashed migrations to allow unapplied squashes if all their replaced migrations are applied\n\nThe system ensures that squash migrations are transparent to the database while maintaining complete dependency tracking and validation across all migration states."
}

